Collaborative editing allows multiple users to edit the same document simultaneously without conflicts. The two main approaches are Operational Transformation (OT) and CRDTs.

**Operational Transformation (OT) — Used by Google Docs:**
Each edit is an operation (insert/delete at position). When concurrent operations conflict, transform one against the other before applying.

```java
public class OTEngine {
    // Operation types: INSERT and DELETE
    record Op(String type, int pos, String content) {}

    // Transform op1 assuming op2 was applied first
    public Op transform(Op op1, Op op2) {
        if (op1.type().equals("INSERT") && op2.type().equals("INSERT")) {
            if (op2.pos() <= op1.pos()) {
                // op2 inserted before op1's position, shift right
                return new Op(op1.type(), op1.pos() + op2.content().length(), op1.content());
            }
            return op1;
        }
        if (op1.type().equals("INSERT") && op2.type().equals("DELETE")) {
            if (op2.pos() < op1.pos()) {
                return new Op(op1.type(), op1.pos() - op2.content().length(), op1.content());
            }
            return op1;
        }
        // ... other combinations
        return op1;
    }

    public String apply(String doc, Op op) {
        return switch (op.type()) {
            case "INSERT" -> doc.substring(0, op.pos()) + op.content() + doc.substring(op.pos());
            case "DELETE" -> doc.substring(0, op.pos()) +
                             doc.substring(op.pos() + op.content().length());
            default -> doc;
        };
    }
}
```

**CRDT Approach (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types):**
Each character gets a globally unique ID and a logical position. No server coordination needed — merge is always deterministic.

```python
import uuid

class CRDTDocument:
    def __init__(self):
        # Each char: (unique_id, value, after_id)
        self.chars = []  # sorted by position

    def insert(self, value, after_id=None):
        char_id = str(uuid.uuid4())
        self.chars.append({'id': char_id, 'val': value, 'after': after_id})
        self._sort()
        return char_id

    def delete(self, char_id):
        for c in self.chars:
            if c['id'] == char_id:
                c['tombstone'] = True  # soft delete

    def text(self):
        return ''.join(c['val'] for c in self.chars if not c.get('tombstone'))

    def _sort(self):
        # Sort by causal order using after_id chain
        pass  # Logoot/LSEQ algorithm for ordering
```

**System Architecture:**
```
Clients → WebSocket Server → OT/CRDT Engine
                                  ↓
                           Document Store (Azure Cosmos DB)
                                  ↓
                          History Log (all operations)
```

**Cursor Broadcasting:** Each client sends cursor position as lightweight presence update (not through OT); broadcast to all collaborators via WebSocket.

**Version History:** Store each operation in an append-only log. Replay from snapshot + operations to restore any past state.

**Conflict Resolution Trade-offs:**
- OT: lower storage, complex server-side transform logic, requires central server
- CRDT: eventually consistent P2P, higher storage (tombstones, IDs), simpler merge

**Word Online uses OT** with a central server maintaining the canonical document state. Each client sends operations; server transforms and broadcasts confirmed ops.

An object pool reuses expensive-to-create objects (DB connections, parsers, threads) to avoid repeated allocation/GC overhead.

**Core Implementation:**
```java
import java.util.concurrent.BlockingQueue;
import java.util.concurrent.LinkedBlockingQueue;
import java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicInteger;

public class ObjectPool<T> {
    private final BlockingQueue<T> pool;
    private final PoolFactory<T> factory;
    private final int maxSize;
    private final AtomicInteger currentSize = new AtomicInteger(0);

    public interface PoolFactory<T> {
        T create() throws Exception;
        boolean validate(T obj);  // is object still healthy?
        void destroy(T obj);      // cleanup on return/removal
    }

    public ObjectPool(int minSize, int maxSize, PoolFactory<T> factory) throws Exception {
        this.factory = factory;
        this.maxSize = maxSize;
        this.pool = new LinkedBlockingQueue<>(maxSize);
        // Pre-warm with minSize objects
        for (int i = 0; i < minSize; i++) {
            T obj = factory.create();
            pool.offer(obj);
            currentSize.incrementAndGet();
        }
    }

    public T borrow(long timeoutMs) throws Exception {
        T obj = pool.poll(); // try non-blocking first
        if (obj != null) {
            return validate(obj);
        }
        // Create new if under max
        if (currentSize.get() < maxSize) {
            if (currentSize.incrementAndGet() <= maxSize) {
                return factory.create();
            }
            currentSize.decrementAndGet();
        }
        // Wait for an object to be returned
        obj = pool.poll(timeoutMs, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS);
        if (obj == null) throw new RuntimeException("Pool exhausted: timeout");
        return validate(obj);
    }

    private T validate(T obj) throws Exception {
        if (factory.validate(obj)) return obj;
        factory.destroy(obj);
        currentSize.decrementAndGet();
        return factory.create(); // replace with fresh object
    }

    public void returnToPool(T obj) {
        if (!factory.validate(obj)) {
            factory.destroy(obj);
            currentSize.decrementAndGet();
            return;
        }
        if (!pool.offer(obj)) {
            // Pool full (shouldn't happen), destroy excess
            factory.destroy(obj);
            currentSize.decrementAndGet();
        }
    }

    public void shutdown() {
        T obj;
        while ((obj = pool.poll()) != null) {
            factory.destroy(obj);
        }
    }
}
```

