**Production Considerations:**
- **Eviction policy:** background thread evicts idle objects beyond minSize (HikariCP checks every 30s)
- **Leak detection:** track borrow time; log warning if object not returned within N seconds
- **Metrics:** pool size, active borrows, wait time, timeouts — expose via Micrometer/Prometheus
- **HikariCP** (best Java DB pool): uses lock-free ConcurrentBag, sub-microsecond borrow time

Multi-tenant SaaS must isolate customer data while sharing infrastructure to reduce costs. The three main strategies represent different trade-offs between isolation, cost, and complexity.

**Strategy 1: Separate Database per Tenant (Highest Isolation)**
```
Tenant A → Database A (dedicated)
Tenant B → Database B (dedicated)

Pros: Complete data isolation, easy compliance (GDPR, HIPAA)
      Independent scaling, no noisy neighbor
Cons: High cost, complex schema migrations (run N migrations)
      Connection pool overhead (1000 tenants = 1000 DB pools)
```

**Strategy 2: Separate Schema per Tenant**
```sql
-- Each tenant gets their own schema in shared DB
CREATE SCHEMA tenant_abc;
CREATE TABLE tenant_abc.orders (...);

CREATE SCHEMA tenant_xyz;
CREATE TABLE tenant_xyz.orders (...);
```
- Middle ground: shared DB infrastructure, logical isolation
- PostgreSQL supports this natively; good for 100s of tenants

**Strategy 3: Shared Schema with tenant_id Column (Most Common)**
```sql
CREATE TABLE orders (
    order_id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
    tenant_id UUID NOT NULL,  -- every table has this
    -- ... other columns
    INDEX idx_tenant_order (tenant_id, order_id)
);

-- Row Level Security (PostgreSQL)
ALTER TABLE orders ENABLE ROW LEVEL SECURITY;
CREATE POLICY tenant_isolation ON orders
    USING (tenant_id = current_setting('app.tenant_id')::UUID);
```

